Kim Yong Nam concludes Vietnam visit 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Hanoi, July 14 (KCNA correspondent) -- Kim Yong Nam, President of the Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly, left Hanoi by a special plane on July 14 after wrapping up his 4-day official goodwill visit to Vietnam.
 He was farewelled by Vietnamese President Tran Duc Luong at the presidency that day.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They expressed belief that Kim's Vietnam visit would mark an important occasion in further strengthening and developing the friendly and cooperative relations between the DPRK and Vietnam. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 While staying in Vietnam Kim Yong Nam visited various places of Hanoi and Haiphong. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 On leaving Vietnam, he sent a message of thanks to president Tran Duc Luong.

KCTU starts solidarity action 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 15 (KCNA) -- The Taegu regional headquarters of the South Korean Confederation of Trade Unions launched a solidarity action on July 12 to support those workers in strike including those of the Daewoo Motor Company and the workers of those enterprises struggling against restructuring, according to Yonhap News from Seoul.
 The organization fixed July 12 as a "day of solidarity with workers in Taegu out to win final victory in the 2001 struggle for higher wage and collective contract and condemn capitalists of worst type." Then they staged a solidarity action in front of the main building of an enterprise in Talsong industrial zone with more than 500 unionists of the company attending. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 At least 100 unionists affiliated to the Daewoo Motor Company will reportedly join the unionists of the federation of metallurgical industrial trade unions who came from all parts of South Korea to Inchon to hold a meeting of metallurgical workers to have job security guaranteed. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The "confederation of national consultative councils of civil servants workshops" (Jongongryon) entered into a sit-in strike in Myongdong cathedral on July 11. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 That day, the Jongongryon called a press conference at which it denounced the prosecution's issue of warrant for arrest of its four leading members on charges of spearheading a meeting of civil servants as an "anachronistic suppression of workers which could be seen only under a military regime."

Kim Yong Nam calls on Vietnamese party leader 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Hanoi, July 14 (KCNA correspondent) -- Kim Yong Nam, President of the Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly, today paid a courtesy call on Nong Duc Manh, General Secretary of the C.C., the Communist Party of Vietnam, at the building of the party central committee.
 On the occasion Nong Duc Manh said that the friendly relations between Vietnam and Korea, provided by President Ho Chi Minh and President Kim Il Sung, have a long tradition. 
 We express heartfelt thanks to the Korean party, government and people for having rendered valuable assistance to the Vietnamese party, government and people in the efforts for national reunification and socialist construction, he said. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kim Yong Nam's current visit will be greatly conducive to the development of the bilateral ties of friendship, Nong said, stressing: the Vietnamese Communist Party, government and people will do their best to further consolidate and develop the traditional relations of friendship and cooperation between the two parties, countries and peoples. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Highly estimating the signal achievements made by the Korean people in the building of the party, the state and the economy under the army-first revolutionary leadership of Kim Jong Il, the General Secretary expressed the belief that they would achieve a greater victory in the sacred cause of building a powerful and prosperous nation and reunifying the country independently and peacefully in the spirit of the June 15 North-South Joint Declaration. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He stressed the need to strengthen mutual solidarity in the interests of the two peoples and for regional and global peace and security.

Kim Yong Nam arrives in Vientiane 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Vientiane, July 14 (KCNA correspondent) -- Kim Yong Nam, President of the Presidium of the Supreme People's Assembly of the DPRK, on July 14 arrived in Vientiane by a special plane to pay an official goodwill visit to the Lao People's Democratic Republic at the invitation of Lao President Khamtay Siphandone.
 A welcome ceremony was held at the presidency of Laos. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present there were President Khamtay Siphandone, deputy prime minister and foreign minister Somsavath Lengsavath and other officials concerned. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kim Yong Nam in company with Khamtay Siphandone reviewed a guard of honour of the Lao People's Army.

Japan's wrong decision on history textbooks accused 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 15 (KCNA) -- The Japanese authorities on July 9 adopted a decision turning down the strong demand of peoples at home and abroad for rewriting the junior middle school history textbooks, which distort Japan's history of aggression.
 They claim that the decision was made in "deep consideration" of Japan's stance toward the revision of the controversial textbooks. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Commenting on it, Rodong Sinmun today says: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Japanese government approved the controversial history textbooks at its examination, and has refused to meet the strong demand from people at home and abroad for their revision. This is intended to cover up Japan's past crimes and evade the apology and compensation for them and, furthermore, infuse the idea of aggression into the younger Japanese for overseas aggression and thus attain its wild design for "Greater East Asia Coprosperity Sphere" at any cost it failed to do in the past. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 After all, the "decision adopted in deep consideration" means that the Japanese authorities have taken everything into serious consideration to achieve their ambition for overseas aggression. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Japanese authorities should lend an ear to the voices of the Asian people who suffered immeasurable damage due to the Japanese imperialists in the past, and drop their shameless position not to redress and apologize for the past crimes while distorting them.
